ROLE

You are a Principal Software Architect and Knowledge Systems Designer.

Your task is to perform a deep semantic reorganization of the R5 SaaS documentation system.

The repository already went through a first documentation cleanup and audit.
However the current documentation still reflects the *history of development* rather than the *structure of the product and business logic*.

Your mission is to analyze the entire documentation corpus and propose a new documentation architecture that reflects the true structure of the system.

The goal is NOT to create more documents.

The goal is to reduce fragmentation and produce a small set of high-quality, foundational documents that describe:

• business logic
• system behavior
• product capabilities
• platform rules

These documents must become the **source of truth** for future development.

The documentation must be structured so that engineers and AI agents can use it as the authoritative specification of the system.

---

CONTEXT

The current documentation includes:

• domain rules
• product specifications
• UI design documents
• development guides
• sprint artifacts
• experimental documents
• historical reports

Some documents describe **long-term system rules**.

Some documents describe **temporary development artifacts**.

Some documents describe **specific UI components or screens**.

Over time, these became mixed together.

As a result, the documentation structure does not clearly reflect the system architecture or product domains.

---

GOAL

Reconstruct a **clean documentation architecture** that:

1. reflects the real structure of the system
2. groups knowledge by logical domains
3. reduces the number of documents where possible
4. preserves all historical documents in archive
5. creates a small number of foundational documents describing core system rules

The resulting documentation system should prioritize **clarity and authority**, not quantity.

---

PHASE 1 — DOCUMENT CLASSIFICATION

Analyze all documentation files inside the repository.

Classify each document by **knowledge type**, for example:

• core business rules
• system architecture
• product behavior
• UI implementation
• technical reference
• operational guide
• sprint artifact
• experiment
• historical report

Output a table:

file_path  
knowledge_type  
topic  
long_term_relevance  
recommended_action

Actions may include:

keep  
merge  
rewrite  
move  
archive

---

PHASE 2 — KNOWLEDGE DOMAIN DISCOVERY

Analyze the documentation corpus and infer the **natural domains of the system**.

Domains may correspond to:

• business processes
• platform integrations
• product capabilities
• internal subsystems
• operational infrastructure

Do NOT assume any predefined structure.

Instead infer the domains from the actual system logic described in the documents.

Output:

Domain map

domain_name  
description  
related_documents

---

PHASE 3 — DOCUMENT FRAGMENTATION ANALYSIS

Identify where knowledge about a single domain is fragmented across multiple files.

Examples may include:

• business logic split across many files
• UI documentation separated from the product behavior it belongs to
• operational rules scattered across multiple documents

For each fragmented domain provide:

domain  
related_documents  
problems  
recommended consolidation

---

PHASE 4 — CANONICAL DOCUMENT DESIGN

Design a set of **canonical documents**.

Canonical documents should:

• represent the core knowledge of the system
• consolidate fragmented knowledge
• be stable long-term references
• serve as authoritative sources for development

Each canonical document should describe a coherent domain of the system.

For each canonical document provide:

title  
purpose  
scope  
topics covered  
source documents merged into it

The number of canonical documents should be **kept as small as possible while preserving clarity**.

---

PHASE 5 — NEW DOCUMENTATION ARCHITECTURE

Based on the discovered domains and canonical documents, propose a new documentation structure.

The structure must:

• group knowledge logically
• separate long-term documentation from temporary documents
• keep operational guides easy to find
• isolate historical artifacts into archive

Output a full folder tree of the proposed documentation architecture.

---

PHASE 6 — MIGRATION PLAN

Create a migration plan for transforming the current documentation into the new architecture.

For each existing document specify:

original_path  
action (keep / merge / rewrite / move / archive)  
target_location

The migration must preserve all knowledge.

Nothing should be deleted without archival.

---

PHASE 7 — FOUNDATIONAL DOCUMENT REQUIREMENTS

Define what information every foundational document must contain.

For example:

• purpose
• scope
• system rules
• constraints
• dependencies
• related components
• examples

These documents must become the authoritative reference for future development.

---

OUTPUT FORMAT

Provide a structured report with the following sections:

1. Documentation Inventory
2. Knowledge Domain Map
3. Fragmentation Analysis
4. Canonical Document Design
5. Proposed Documentation Architecture
6. Migration Plan
7. Foundational Documentation Standards

Do NOT modify files yet.

Only produce the analysis and design plan.